did.abstract: Pauline Bart is a feminist sociologist and former professor of sociology and psychiatry. From the 1960s to the 1990s, Bart was active in many feminist and civil rights issues, including anti-pornography protests, sexual assault and rape law reform, Jewish and middle-aged women's advocacy, reproductive rights, and violence against women. The Pauline Bart papers consists of personal files, including correspondence, appointment books, diaries, peer-reviewed mansucripts for which Bart served as a referee, subject files for conferences Bart attended, and other material related to Bart's personal and professional life; drafts and published copies of articles, papers, and reviews written by Bart; papers related to classes taught by Bart at the University of Illinois in Chicago, the University of California at Los Angeles, and other institutions; and research files, including interview transcripts and other papers related to the Jane Collective, transcripts of interviews with 94 survivors of sexual assault or attempted rape and other papers related to Bart's study of rape avoidance; interview transcripts and other papers related to a study of depression, and other research files on topics such as pornography, depression, violence against women, the Illinois sexual assault statute, feminism, rape, and homosexuality.

bioghist.head: Historical note
bioghist.p: Pauline Bart is a feminist sociologist and former professor of sociology and psychiatry. From the 1960s to the 1990s, Bart was active in many feminist and civil rights issues, including anti-pornography protests, sexual assault and rape law reform, Jewish and middle-aged women's advocacy, reproductive rights, and violence against women.

Bart received her Ph.D. in sociology from the University of California at Los Angeles in 1967. After struggling to find a long-term position for several years, she became a professor at the University of Illinois in Chicago, where she remained from 1970-1992. Bart experienced a turbulent relationship with UIC administrators throughout her time there, and as she rose through the ranks of professorship to achieve tenure, she struggled to attain salary equity with her male counterparts. In 1992, Bart was implicated in a controversy involving one of her male students, Donald Dixon, who accused Bart of making discriminatory remarks against men and characterizing him in racist and sexist terms to his fellow classmates. Although Bart denied these allegations, her classes were reassigned and her relationship with the University of Illinois at Chicago ended over the matter. Bart then served as a lecturer at the University of California at Los Angeles before retiring in 1995. She currently lives in Morrisville, North Carolina.

accessrestrict.p: Boxes 35-39 and 90-91 are closed to researchers until 2039.

scopecontent.head: Collection Overview
scopecontent.p: The Pauline Bart papers are arranged into four series. The Personal Files Series contains correspondence, appointment books, diaries, peer-reviewed mansucripts for which Bart served as a referee, and other material related to Bart's personal and professional life, including papers related to her struggles to achieve salary equity and documentation of the 1992 controversy which led to her termination from the University of Illinois at Chicago. Also included in this series are subject files for conferences Bart attended to present papers or serve on panels. The Writings Series contains drafts and copies of reviews, written by Bart, of articles and books published by various authors; drafts of Bart's book, Stopping Rape: Successful Survival Strategies, and other papers related to the book's publication; drafts and published copies of articles and academic papers written by Bart; and other materials related to her writings, including book contracts, reprint requests, and reviews of her work. The Teaching Materials Series contains papers related to classes taught by Bart at the University of Illinois in Chicago, the University of California at Los Angeles, and other institutions. Materials include syllabi, lists and copies of course readings, student papers, and other papers. The Research Files Series contains interview transcripts, content analysis, and other papers related to the Jane Collective, which Bart researched in pursuit of her article "Seizing the Means of Reproduction: An Illegal Feminist Abortion Collective - How and Why it Worked;" materials related to Stopping Rape: Successful Survival Strategies, including transcripts of interviews with 94 survivors of sexual assault or attempted rape, notebooks containing content analysis of the interviews, grant applications and drafts, Viva rape questionnaires, and other papers; interview transcripts and other papers related to a study of depression; and other research files on topics such as pornography, depression, violence against women, the Illinois sexual assault statute, feminism, rape, and homosexuality. The Audiotapes series contains recordings of talks given by Bart, conference sessions, presentations, interviews, and classes conducted at the University of Illinois at Chicago. Also included are recordings of 9 interviews with members of the Jane Collective (see box 90).

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Materials in the Personal Files Series are arranged alphabetically by folder title, with the exception of the Correspondence and Notebooks and Diaries Subseries, which are arranged chronologically. Materials in the Writings, Teaching Materials, and Research Files Series are arranged alphabetically by folder title, with the exception of the Other Research Files Subseries, which is arranged alphabetically by subject. Original folder titles have, for the most part, been retained.
Some original documents may have been replaced by redacted photocopies to protect personally identifying information.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Personal Files Series contains correspondence, appointment books, diaries, peer-reviewed mansucripts for which Bart served as a referee, and other material related to Bart's personal and professional life, including papers related to her struggles to achieve salary equity and documentation of the 1992 controversy which led to her termination from the University of Illinois at Chicago.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Correspondence Subseries includes Bart's personal and professional correspondence. Much of the correspondence relates to Bart's plans to travel to conferences or universities to lecture about her research. There are also letters from sociologists, professors, and other scholars requesting copies of Bart's writings or more information on her research. There is very little family correspondence.

While most of the correspondence in this subseries is professional in nature, personal correspondence reflects the turbulent relationships among members of the feminist movement throughout the second half of the 20th century. As the movement expanded, feminists often disagreed with each other on various issues, and these disagreements can be seen in several volatile exchanges in this subseries, in which Bart was either directly or tangentially involved. Some of Bart's more frequent correspondents include feminists such as Catherine MacKinnon, Andrea Dworkin, and Phyllis Chelser.

Particularly in the late 1980s and early 1990s, Bart struggled with her own feminist identity, and she felt as though feminism was generally becoming more conservative while she was becoming more radical. During this time, Bart also struggled with her feelings regarding her own sexuality and her relationships with women, depression, and thoughts of suicide, all of which are reflected in her personal correspondence.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Notebooks and Diaries Subseries contains Bart's address book, appointment books, autograph albums, diaries, and a notebook. The two autograph albums in this subseries were compiled during Bart's time at P.S. 235 and Winthrop Junior High School in Brooklyn, New York. Bart kept diaries regularly from childhood throughout her adult life. The diaries' contents are often varied and irregular, including dated entries as well as notes from presentation, phone numbers, and reminders. Bart frequently recorded her dreams.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Refereed Manuscripts Subseries contains copies of articles for which Bart served as a peer reviewer, review sheets containing her comments on these manuscripts, and occasional correspondence with journal editors.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Conferences Subseries contains subject files for conferences that Bart attended, either as a speaker or as a regular attendee. In cases where Bart traveled to a conference to present a paper, drafts of these papers may be included. Frequently attended conferences include the annual meetings of the American Sociological Association (ASA), National Women's Studies Association (NWSA), Child Sexual Assault Services Network (CSASN), Society for the Study of Social Problems (SSSP), and Sociologists for Women in Society.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains drafts of Stopping Rape: Successful Survival Strategies, a book Bart co-authored with Patricia H. O'Brien, and other papers related to the book's publication. Published in 1985, Stopping Rape expanded upon research Bart conducted in 1977, when she interviewed 94 survivors of rape or attempted rape in order to generate a list of survival strategies. In addition to chapter drafts, this subseries also includes advertising and publicity related to the book's publication and the underlying research study.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Articles and Academic Paper Subseries contains drafts and printed copies of published and unpublished academic articles and papers written or co-authored by Bart, as well as correspondence, publication information, and other papers related to some articles. Included in this series are drafts and copies of some of Bart's more notable works, including "Portnoy's Mother's Complaint," which grew from Bart's research on depression for her dissertation, "Depression in Middle-Aged Women;" "The Battered Data Syndrome," an article on interpersonal violence and spousal abuse co-authored by Bart, Elizabeth H. Pleck, Joseph H. Pleck, and Marlyn Grossman in response to Suzanne K. Steinmetz's research on battered husbands; "A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Orifice," an article about sexist language in gynecology textbooks co-authored by Bart and Diana Scully, and "Seizing the Means of Reproduction," the product of Bart's reserach on the Jane Collective, a feminist underground abortion service in Chicago in the early 1970s.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Jane Collective Research Subseries contains papers related to Bart's research on the Abortion Counseling Service of Women's Liberation, also known as the Jane Collective, a feminist underground abortion service operating in Chicago, Illinois from 1969-1973. Founded by University of Chicago student Heather Booth, the Jane Collective provided more than 11,000 women with abortions and abortion counseling prior to abortion being legalized by Roe v. Wade in 1973.

Bart interviewed members of the Jane Collective in pursuit of her article, "Seizing the Means of Reproduction." The materials in this subseries include interview transcripts, Bart's content analysis and notes on the interviews, drafts and draft fragments of "Seizing the Means of Reproduction," and some correspondence. Some interviews also include audio recordings. See the Audiotapes Series for more information.

scopecontent.p: The Rape Avoidance Research Subseries contains materials related to Bart's book, Stopping Rape: Successful Survival Strategies. Papers include transcripts of anonymous interviews with 94 surivors of rape and attempted rape, including 9 pilot interviews, code books, materials related to grants that funded the study, interview schedules, notebooks containing Bart's content analysis and notes on the interviews, Viva Magazine Rape Questionnaires, and other papers.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Depression Study Subseries contains materials related to the study that Bart conducted in pursuit of her dissertation, "Depression in Middle-Aged Women." Papers include interview transcripts, notes, a research proposal, and other materials.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Other Research Files Subseries contains subject files on various topics related to feminism, women's health, psychology and other subjects. Topics include pornography, depression, violence against women, the Illinois sexual assault statute, feminism, rape, homosexuality, and other subjects. Papers tend to consist largely of clippings and notes on these subjects, with occasional correspondence and other materials.
